IMPORTANT: You MUST respond with ONLY a valid JSON object using this structure:
{
  "type": "existing"|"new"|"rule",
  "categoryId": "string", // Required for "existing"; for "rule" include only when the matched rule sets a category, omit when the rule says "leave uncategorized"
  "ruleName": "string", // Required if matching rule
  "newCategory": { // Required if suggesting new category
    "name": "string",
    "groupName": "string",
    "groupIsNew": boolean
  },
  "confidence": 0.85 // Required: your confidence in this classification, from 0.0 (no idea) to 1.0 (certain)
}

If a rule renders as "→ leave uncategorized", that rule explicitly tells you NOT to assign a category. Match it with type "rule" and the ruleName, and OMIT categoryId — do not invent one and do not fall back to "new".

Set confidence LOW (below 0.6) when:
- The payee name is cryptic, abbreviated, or looks like an internal code
- You are unsure whether to use an existing category or create a new one
- The merchant is not well-known or the transaction purpose is ambiguous

Set confidence HIGH (above 0.8) when:
- The payee is a well-known brand/merchant you are certain about
- The category match is obvious (e.g., supermarket → Groceries)

DO NOT output any text before or after the JSON. Your entire response must be a valid, parsable JSON object.

Examples:
{"type": "existing", "categoryId": "abc123", "confidence": 0.95}
{"type": "rule", "categoryId": "def456", "ruleName": "Coffee Shop", "confidence": 1.0}
{"type": "rule", "ruleName": "Amazon leave uncategorized", "confidence": 1.0}
{"type": "new", "newCategory": {"name": "Pet Supplies", "groupName": "Pets", "groupIsNew": true}, "confidence": 0.7}

